  "prompt": "How much of myoglobin is there in pork and how much of Iron is there in the myoglobin in weight?",
  "response": "The myoglobin content in pork typically ranges from 2 to 10 milligrams per gram of meat, depending on factors such as the age of the animal and the muscle type. Myoglobin is a protein that primarily stores oxygen in muscle cells and gives meat its red color.\n\nMyoglobin is made up of a heme group containing iron. Each heme group in myoglobin contains one iron atom. The molecular mass of myoglobin is about 17,000 Dalton (or grams per mole), while the molecular mass of the heme group is about 616 Dalton. Within the heme group, iron atoms constitute approximately 55.8 Dalton.\n\nCalculating from this information:\n1. If you assume the average myoglobin content is 5 milligrams per gram of meat (as an example within the range):\n    - 1 gram of pork has 5 milligrams of myoglobin.\n    - Molecular mass of myoglobin is ~17,000 Dalton.\n\n2. Calculating the proportion of iron in myoglobin:\n    - Iron mass (Fe) in heme group = 55.8 Dalton.\n    - Proportion of iron in myoglobin = (mass of iron in heme group) / (total mass of myoglobin)\n    - For heme group = 55.8 / 17,000 \u2248 0.0033 or 0.33%.\n\n3. Calculating weight of iron:\n    - In 5 milligrams of myoglobin: 5 mg * 0.33% \u2248 0.0165 milligrams of iron.\n    - Thus, each 1 gram of pork roughly contains 0.0165 milligrams of iron within its myoglobin content.\n\nRemember that these values are approximations and can fluctuate based on given examples and specific details not accounted for in general calculations.",
